{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522039"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:40:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:40:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13792"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13792"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.28,0.53,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81301"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6410"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66643"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36027"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44397"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81301"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of fever, headache and muscle pains. He has also developed a widespread skin rash over the past two days. He works as a sheep farmer in rural Australia. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a temperature of 39.2\u00b0C, pulse rate 110/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. He has a non-pruritic, maculopapular rash over his trunk and extremities (Image). The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lyme disease","Rocky Mountain spotted fever","Q fever","Dengue fever","Typhoid fever"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQ fever\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by the bacterium \u003Cem\u003ECoxiella burnetii\u003C/em\u003E and is strongly associated with exposure to livestock, particularly sheep, cattle, and goats. The patient\u2019s occupation as a sheep farmer in rural Australia places him at high risk. Clinical features such as fever, headache, and myalgia are typical of Q fever. While a a widespread maculopapular rash is less common in Q fever, it can occur. This presentation is therefore considered atypical but still consistent with Q fever based on occupational and epidemiological factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELyme disease\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by \u003Cem\u003EBorrelia burgdorferi\u003C/em\u003E and transmitted by ticks. While it can cause fever, headache, and myalgia, the erythema migrans rash typically appears at the site of the tick bite and is localized rather than widespread. Lyme disease is not endemic in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERocky Mountain spotted fever (RMSF)\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by \u003Cem\u003ERickettsia rickettsii\u003C/em\u003E and transmitted by ticks. It is not found in Australia and causes a petechial rash that starts on the wrists and ankles and spreads centrally, differing from the widespread maculopapular rash in this case. Australian spotted fever (\u003Cem\u003ERickettsia australis\u003C/em\u003E), which can cause fever, headache, and a rash, is reported in northern Queensland. However, it is less likely here due to the patient\u2019s location in a livestock farming region and the absence of clear tick exposure. Given Q fever\u2019s stronger link to livestock and its higher incidence in Australia, it remains the more likely diagnosis in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDengue fever \u003C/strong\u003Eis a mosquito-borne viral illness that commonly causes fever, headache, and myalgia. The rash in dengue typically appears later in the illness and is erythematous with a pattern described as \u0027islands of white in a sea of red.\u0027 Dengue is not endemic in rural Australia, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETyphoid fever\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by \u003Cem\u003ESalmonella typhi\u003C/em\u003E, can present with fever and headache but is often accompanied by gastrointestinal symptoms such as abdominal pain and diarrhoea. The rose spots of typhoid fever are generally sparse, localized to the trunk, and not typically widespread as described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Q fever typically presents with fever, headache, myalgia, and a widespread skin rash.","Q fever is caused by Coxiella burnetii and is often associated with exposure to livestock or their products."],"references":["Hamad G. Ranmuthugala G. Q fever awareness in Australia: A scoping review. Aust N Z J Public Health. 2023; 47:1-17.","Eldin C, Melenotte C, Mediannikov O, et al. From Q Fever to Coxiella burnetii Infection: a Paradigm Change. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2017; 30:115-90"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66643"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13792"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20734"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20734"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cSWfbghEbAesmRrcyk0FVXZctHoAGO.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cSWfbghEbAesmRrcyk0FVXZctHoAGO.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66643"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-25T19:49:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-25T19:50:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6410"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81301"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4961"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4966","links":{"self":"https://ap